        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>S. Solis Cohen Esqre<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I have just received your note&#44; and I<lb/> answer immediately.<lb/></p>
            <p>To do the questions you put to me full<lb/> justice would be to indite a lengthy <del>essay</del> dissertation.<lb/>  But <del>as</del> judging that brevity&#44; which does not involve am&#45;<lb/>&#45;biguity&#44; may be <del>is always</del> preferable&#44; I will simply say<lb/> 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> The report that Maimonides embraced Ma&#45;<lb/><sic>homadanism</sic> was circulated by an Arabic author&#44;<lb/> and <del>then</del> carelessly repeated by some Jewish writers.<lb/>  It has been stated that during a persecution under<lb/> the Almohades&#44; <del>our Moses</del> the Sage of Cordova saved his life by<lb/> feigning Islamism.  No author of repute<lb/> among the Hebrew people has made allusion to the<lb/> circumstance.  <del>Surely</del> It does not stand to reason<lb/> that the man who exhorted the Jews of South<lb/> Arabia in his famous letter &#40;Iggerite Teman&#91;&#63;&#93;&#41; to<lb/> tear themselves away&#44; if necessary&#44; from their own<lb/> country and homes&#44; to relinquish property&#44;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>and wander in deserts&#44; rather than <sic>yeild</sic> to the<lb/> pressure of the time&#44; and abjure the ancestral<lb/> belief&#44; that he himself would be guilty of the sin <del>of duplicity</del> <del>apostacy</del><lb/> <del>or even duplicity</del> he so eagerly wished to prevent.<lb/>  2d After the death of Maimonides&#44; the Hebrew<lb/> translation of his book&#44; More Nebuchim&#44; which<lb/> he wrote in Arabic for the instruction of a<lb/> favorite pupil&#44; spread abroad.  It met with<lb/> a decided opposition&#59; but none attacked it<lb/> so violently as a Rabbi Solomon of Mont&#45;<lb/>&#45;pellier.  The author was charged with heresy&#44;<lb/> and as anathema hurled against his readers.<lb/>  The contest <del>took</del> assumed a wide range&#44;<lb/> and the feelings on the side of the accusers and<lb/> the defenders grew very bitter.  Finally&#44; the curse<lb/> of Maimonides&#44; or of freedom of thought succeeded.<lb/>  3d.  So great was the esteem in which the con&#45;<lb/>temporaries of Maimonides of Maimonides<lb/> held the Sage&#44; that in some <del>of their Syna</del><lb/>&#45;gogues the following addition was made<lb/> to the <hi rend="underline">Kaddish</hi>.  &#34;To your life&#45;time&#44; <hi rend="underline">and in the</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">life&#45;time of our teacher Moses the son of Maimon</hi><lb/></p> 
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>may redemption come&#34;¬ù &#38;c.<lb/></p>
            <p>4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Orthodox Jews of the present age are divided<lb/> in opinion.  Some regret the fact that<lb/> Maimonides was undeservedly <del>too</del> fond of Anstolebar&#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> philosophy&#44; and <del>that</del> therefore he shaped his ideas<lb/> in a measure&#44; after the model left by the<lb/> Hagerite.  Others rejoice at his having shown<lb/> that a Jew can give his thoughts ample<lb/> scope and still remain loyal to his faith.<lb/> All&#44; however&#44; hold that the second Moses<lb/> in veneration for the invaluable service he<lb/> rendered Hebrew literature&#44; and for the lasting<lb/> <del>honor his personal merits and</del> lustre his most extensive<lb/> writings and <del>his</del> personal merits <del>inflicted</del> shed upon<lb/> the nation.<lb/></p>
            <p>5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Maimonides did not blindly adhere to the<lb/> views advanced by <sic>Aristolte</sic>.  He rejected the<lb/> idea of <hi rend="underline">eternity of matter</hi>&#44; unequivocally<lb/> admitting that nothing existed before the<lb/> Divine fiat brought forth <del>creation</del> the universe.<lb/>  Regarding Immortality&#44; he approaches Ave&#44;<lb/>roes&#44; but very slightly.  He seems to<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>think that the moving spout whereat in<lb/> man from <del>his</del> the hour of his birth is not the<lb/> undying soul&#44; capable of enjoying bliss&#59; that<lb/> it is only a tendency to human perfectibility&#44;<lb/> instrument&#44; as it were&#44; worthy together with the intellectual<lb/> faculties for the creation of a soul&#44; which will<lb/> approach the essence of all perfection&#44; when <del>disappointed</del> disconnected<lb/> from the body.  Hence&#44; some have argued&#44; that<lb/> the Sage of Cordova denies the illiterate Immortality.<lb/>  The question is too abstruse&#44; and I will not dare<lb/> <del>to</del> decide <del>wh</del> of the deduction is <del>altogether unable</del> supported by<lb/> strong grounds.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping that my short reply&#44; will be of<lb/> some service&#44;  I remain<lb/>
                Yours truly<lb/>
                S Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>Sept 6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1878<lb/></p>
